docs.abstract: Ten years ago, the Olori Sisterhood was a small-time “political sorority.” Now they’re ready for a seat at the table.
docs.snippet: Ten years ago, the Olori Sisterhood was a small-time “political sorority.” Now they’re ready for a seat at the table.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last November, when Democratic presidential candidates were still jockeying for the nomination, before the coronavirus pandemic killed more than 250,000 Americans and fervent protests against police brutality swept the nation, Senator Kamala Harris of California appeared before a group of mostly Black women in South Carolina to file officially for the state’s critical primary.

headline.main: How a Brooklyn Sisterhood of Black Women Became National Power Brokers
headline.print_headline: Ready for Their Seat at the Table

docs.abstract: A quiet battle over retail space is a modern fight for the soul of Black Los Angeles.
docs.snippet: A quiet battle over retail space is a modern fight for the soul of Black Los Angeles.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — Even as the post-George Floyd national focus on the grand battle against systemic racism and all things Black plateaus, ground battles for equity that have been fought for decades continue. One such fight here in Los Angeles is reaching a critical point.

docs.abstract: Prosecutors introduced evidence at the hearing of the son having sent racist text messages, while Mr. Arbery’s mother wailed in court as a video of her son’s killing was played.
docs.snippet: Prosecutors introduced evidence at the hearing of the son having sent racist text messages, while Mr. Arbery’s mother wailed in court as a video of her son’s killing was played.
docs.lead_paragraph: A judge denied bond on Friday to the white father and son charged with murder in the killing of Ahmaud Arbery, the 25-year-old Black man shot by the son after they chased him down a quiet road in Georgia.

headline.main: Judge Denies Bond to Father and Son Charged With Killing Ahmaud Arbery
headline.print_headline: Duo Charged With Killing Black Jogger in Georgia Are Denied Bond

docs.abstract: About a fifth of all voters said the protests were the single most important factor in their decision at the ballot box, according to a new survey.
docs.snippet: About a fifth of all voters said the protests were the single most important factor in their decision at the ballot box, according to a new survey.
docs.lead_paragraph: The protests that broke out after the police killing of George Floyd in May were some of the biggest racial justice marches organized in decades. In the early weeks, polling showed broad and deep support for them across the country.

headline.main: Voters Say Black Lives Matter Protests Were Important. They Disagree On Why.
headline.print_headline: Protests Swayed Voters, Either as Inspiration or as Intimidation

byline.original: By Sabrina Tavernise and John Eligon

docs.abstract: Yet Philadelphia, Milwaukee and Detroit have become the targets of G.O.P. allegations of voting shenanigans.
docs.snippet: Yet Philadelphia, Milwaukee and Detroit have become the targets of G.O.P. allegations of voting shenanigans.
docs.lead_paragraph: In Pennsylvania, much of President Trump’s attention since the election has focused on Philadelphia, where he has baselessly insisted there is a “mountain of corruption.” In Michigan, litigation by Mr. Trump’s campaign has concentrated on Detroit, where Republican poll watchers say they felt intimidated by election workers in Black Lives Matter apparel. And in Wisconsin, legal challenges and rumors have circled around Milwaukee, where one internet conspiracy  theory turns on a briefly misplaced flash drive of election results.

headline.main: The Cities Central to Fraud Conspiracy Theories Didn’t Cost Trump the Election
headline.print_headline: Conspiracy Theories Center on Cities That Didn’t Cost Trump the Election

docs.abstract: President Trump comfortably carried Chaska, Minn., in 2016. This time, he lost by nine percentage points — a dramatic shift that similarly played out in suburban counties across the country.
docs.snippet: President Trump comfortably carried Chaska, Minn., in 2016. This time, he lost by nine percentage points — a dramatic shift that similarly played out in suburban counties across the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHASKA, Minn. — As some protests over police brutality and systemic racism descended into vandalism and looting in Minneapolis over the summer, President Trump insisted that he was the candidate to restore “law and order” to the city. In the nearby suburb of Chaska, Minn., Mike Magusin bristled. In his view, he said, the president had fueled the unrest.

headline.main: How a Minneapolis Suburb Turned Blue, Despite Trump’s Law-and-Order Pitch
headline.print_headline: How a Minneapolis Suburb Turned Blue

docs.abstract: MINNEAPOLIS — At the site where George Floyd was killed by the Minneapolis police in May, Romell Jernagin said on Friday that persistent issues plaguing his community, such as police brutality and gang activity, were unlikely to be solved by new political leadership.

headline.main: Minneapolis residents say new leaders can’t always solve old problems.

docs.abstract: Representative-elect Cori Bush, a Missouri Democrat, arrived at the new House members orientation Friday wearing a Breonna Taylor face mask.
